`crates/ctx-cage/src/lifecycle/` implements the three-phase execution of one cage run (prepare → run → teardown) behind the single public entry point `execute` in `mod.rs`. Callers hand it a `Resolved` struct (target root, task id, mode, tool paths, `allow_dirty`); everything else — rundir creation, billed-mode gating, proxy/broker setup, `bwrap` invocation, cleanup — is internal.

The phases share a strict handoff contract: `prepare::prepare_run` returns a `Prep` (rundir, rules file, mask file, optional `ClaudeRuntime`) that both `run`/`serve` and `teardown` consume. Any new resource created in `prepare` needs a matching cleanup step in `teardown_run`, which is scoped to deleting only `prep.rundir` and never anything else, and never fails observably (its errors are swallowed, per `execute`'s best-effort teardown guarantee even when `run` fails or the process is killed).

There are two parallel run-phase implementations: `run.rs` (proxy-based, forwards claude's own OAuth token straight through, used with `crate::proxy`) and `serve.rs` (broker-based, brokers only `ctx-access`/`ctx-verify` tool calls via `crate::broker`, allowlisted). Both build a `BwrapConfig` from `crate::bwrap` and exec `bwrap` directly, and both must stay in sync with constants defined in `bwrap.rs` (`API_SOCK_NAME`, `CAGE_BIN`, `CAGE_CLAUDE_CONFIG`, `CAGE_CLAUDE_CRED`, `CAGE_LOCAL_CLAUDE`, `CAGE_RULES_PATH`) — changing a mount point or path constant there requires updating usage in whichever run-phase file relies on it. Which of the two is active/canonical isn't visible from ctx alone; treat both as live and consistent with `mod.rs`'s three-submodule split unless told otherwise.

`prepare_run`'s billed-mode gates (dirty-tree check via `git status --porcelain`, claude runtime/credential resolution) are the only place billed-vs-non-billed branching happens before the run phase; `mod.rs` itself is mode-agnostic. `mod.rs` also owns the one load-bearing pre-step both run implementations depend on implicitly: `target_root` is canonicalized before `prepare_run` ever sees it, because both `bwrap` configs assume absolute binds.

